<section xml:id="C30.S5">
<title>Functions of the Second Kind</title>        
  
        
<para xml:id="C30.S5.p1">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="1" xml:id="C30.S5.p1.s1">
Other solutions of (30.2.1) with <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C30.S5.p1.m1">\mu=m</Math> , <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C30.S5.p1.m2">\lambda=\lambda^{m}_{n}\left(\gamma^{2}\right)</Math> , and <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C30.S5.p1.m3">z=x</Math> are <Math equation-number="30.5.1" mode="display" xml:id="C30.S5.E1">\mathsf{Qs}^{m}_{n}\left(x,\gamma^{2}\right), if n=m,m+1,m+2,\dots</Math>.
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="2" sentence-num-in-section="2" xml:id="C30.S5.p1.s2">
They satisfy <Math equation-number="30.5.2" mode="display" xml:id="C30.S5.E2">\mathsf{Qs}^{m}_{n}\left(-x,\gamma^{2}\right)=(-1)^{n-m+1}\mathsf{Qs}^{m}_{n} \left(x,\gamma^{2}\right),</Math> and <Math equation-number="30.5.3" mode="display" xml:id="C30.S5.E3">\mathsf{Qs}^{m}_{n}\left(x,0\right)=\mathsf{Q}^{m}_{n}\left(x\right);</Math> compare §14.3(i).
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="3" sentence-num-in-section="3" xml:id="C30.S5.p1.s3">
Also, <Math equation-number="30.5.4" mode="display" xml:id="C30.S5.E4">\mathscr{W}\left\{\mathsf{Ps}^{m}_{n}\left(x,\gamma^{2}\right),\mathsf{Qs}^{m} _{n}\left(x,\gamma^{2}\right)\right\}=\frac{(n+m)!}{(1-x^{2})(n-m)!}A_{n}^{m}( \gamma^{2})A_{n}^{-m}(\gamma^{2})\quad(\neq 0),</Math> with <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C30.S5.p1.m4">A_{n}^{\pm m}(\gamma^{2})</Math> as in (30.11.4).
</sentence>

</para>
 
<para xml:id="C30.S5.p2">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="4" xml:id="C30.S5.p2.s1">
For further properties see Meixner and Schäfke (1954) and §30.8(ii).
</sentence>

</para>
 
</section>
